	<p class="page-design__our-experience">
        <span>The Good</span>
		<ul class="page-design__our-experience--list">
            <li><strong>The natural beauty is unparallelled.</strong> There were bus rides where we could not take our eyes off the scenery passing us by.</li>
            <li><strong>The Salar de Uyuni alone is worth visiting Bolivia</strong>, in fact many people do just that when they go to South America. It was definitely one of the top three things we did on our entire trip. </li>  
            <li>Bolivia is a great place to treat yourself. Even in the tourist spots you will be spending much less here than any other country. This is the place to get drinks, apps and dessert without breaking the bank. </li>    
        </ul>
	</p>
    <p class="page-design__our-experience">
        <span>The Bad</span>
        <ul class="page-design__our-experience--list">
            <li>We found that in many cities in Bolivia the people seemed rude. This is for many reasons, I’m sure, but one of our tour guides explained one of the reasons to us. <strong>Bolivia is currently the poorest country in South America</strong> and when they see tourists they do not think of the potential economic benefit, they think that we are spoiled and rich. Which, let’s be honest, if we’re travelling we are more privileged than most in Bolivia. This means that when we want to bargain with the vendors it pisses them off. Now, that’s not to say you shouldn’t bargain, but you may have some more trouble here than in other countries.</li>
            <li>That being said, there are a plethora of <strong>kind, amazing individuals</strong> throughout this country, we just found them less prevalent than the other countries we visited.</li>  
            <li><strong>The food is not great.</strong> You will find that most of the food is fried or starch. When they try other foods, such as pizzas or burgers, they do it horribly. I would recommend cooking as much as you can and keeping one eye on TripAdvisor at all times.</li>
            <li>We also know that a lot of our problems stemmed from the fact that we did not speak Spanish when we arrived. You will be taken more seriously if you speak their language.</li>    
        </ul>
    </p>
    <p class="page-design__our-experience">
        <span>The Verdict</span>
        <p class="section-headers__line-highlight section-headers__line-highlight--smaller">
            Overall, we recommend Bolivia. This does depend on the type of traveller you are, but if you are up for a bit of discomfort, the reward is high! At the very minimum, make it down to Uyuni and do the 3 day Salar de Uyuni tour. You will not regret it. 
        </p>
    </p>
