<div class="wrapper wrapper--smaller wrapper__line-spacing">
    <p class="section-headers__new-section" id="tips-and-tricks">
        <span><i class="fa fa-paper-plane fa-lg"></i> Tips and Tricks</span>
    </p>
    <p class="page-design__our-experience">
        <ul class="page-design__our-experience--list">
           <li>
               <strong>Do your research for everything!</strong> This is a general tip, obviously, but it is especially important in Bolivia! There is a huge difference in quality of products (busses, tours) in Bolivia more so than any other country. Check the internet for the best bus companies before going to the station or you will regret it. 
           </li>
           <li>
               <strong>Always keep an eye on your belongings -</strong>Again, always important, but we knew many people who had things stolen from them on busses because they weren’t being careful enough.
           </li>   
           <li>
               <strong>Tipping -</strong> tipping is generally not expected in Bolivia. We liked to leave a little extra when the service was good or food was exceptional. In more touristy areas you may want to tip at fancier restaurants, but anywhere from 5-10% is considered an appropriate tip. <strong>Tipping your tour guide</strong> is widely expected. Often the tour agencies pay their guides poorly and they will rely on your tips. It doesn’t have to be excessive, but if your guide does a good job, show him/her by tipping them. 
           </li>
           <li>
               <strong>Taxis -</strong> taxis in Bolivia are mostly regular cars with a small sign in the windows. Make sure you negotiate the cost before you get in the vehicle. You will be constantly honked at, this is just how they let you know that they are there and available. At first we were annoyed with it, but you get used to it. 
           </li>
           <li>
               <strong>Medication -</strong> Sorochi Pills are a must for almost every city in Bolivia. You will get used to the altitude, but you will need them for the first little bit. Dramamine will also save your life on the long windy bus rides and the Salar de Uyuni trip. 
           </li>
           <li>
               <strong>Bring warm clothes -</strong> Despite the days being warm, the nights can be seriously cold. Make sure to bring a nice warm sweater and even a hat/mits. They are useful at night to sleep, travelling on overnight busses, and when you go on your treks.
           </li>

        </ul>
    </p>
